## \#WednesdayChallenge (\#WedC)

### What it is:
Write a single-post short story in response to a theme chosen weekly (posted with \#WedC or \#WednesdayChallenge hashtags.) 

### How it started:
For more detail [see the App.net Wiki page.](https://github.com/bazbt3/appdotnet_stuff/wiki/WednesdayChallenge)

### How it works:
1. Write a 1 post entry based around the week’s theme, chosen each Wednesday.
2. Post it, remembering to include either the hashtag [\#WedC](https://pnut.io/tags/WedC) (preferred) or [\#WednesdayChallenge](https://pnut.io/tags/WednesdayChallenge) if your muse isn’t being helpful and you need to fill space!

### Deutsch:
* *From [@schmidt_fu’s pnut.io post:](https://posts.pnut.io/64400)*    
> “Guten Abend, nach altem Brauch ([\#WednesdayChallenge](https://pnut.io/tags/WednesdayChallenge)) rufe ich auf, eine kurze Geschichte zu schreiben. Sie passe in 256 Zeichen, trage das Zeichen [\#WedC](https://pnut.io/tags/WedC) oder [\#MitC](https://pnut.io/tags/MitC) und treffe das Thema dieser Woche “Links” (deutsch oder englisch)    
[\#MittwochsChallenge](https://pnut.io/tags/MittwochsChallenge)”

### More:
* An extended version can be posted elsewhere (e.g. your own blog.) Though the challenge starts on Wednesday there are no pressures to hit deadlines - writing runs for the full week. You don’t even have to publicise your involvement, if writing is the thing that spreads your toes. 
* Given the 256-character post limit most people will use \#WedC. The original \#WednesdayChallenge hashtag was abbreviated in response to the inevitable observation that 14 superfluous character of tag is silly.

—

Text of the October 2013 version of the appdotnetwiki.net page extracted from the Wayback Machine archive.
